> Creamy polenta and ragù are a classic pairing you can make extra-fast! Heat
> our precooked polenta, then swirl in sour cream, cream cheese, Parmesan,
> and butter for a luxuriously rich texture. Top it with a hearty tomato ragù
> packed with zucchini, onion, and carrots, and serve crisp ciabatta toasts
> alongside, ready to scoop it all up.

Wash and dry produce.

Trim, peel, and cut @carrots{6%ounce}(trimmed, peeled and cut on a diagonal
into 1⁄2-inch-thick pieces). Halve, peel, and cut @onion{1}(peeled and halved
into 1⁄2-inch-thick wedges). Trim and halve @zucchini{1}(trimmed and halved
lengthwise); cut crosswise into 1⁄2-inch-thick half-moons.

Pat @chicken cutlets{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}, season all over with
@salt{} and @pepper{}. Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a large pan over
medium-high heat. Add chicken or same skin sides down; cook chicken until
cooked through, ~{3-5%minutes} per side, or cook salmon until skin is crisp,
~{5-7%minutes}, then flip and cook until cooked through, ~{1-2%minutes} more.
Turn off heat; transfer to a #plate{}. Wipe out pan.

Heat a large drizzle of cooking oil in a large pan over medium-high heat.
Add carrots, onion, and zucchini; season with @garlic powder{1%teaspoon},
@Italian seasoning{1%tablespoon} (all for 4 servings), salt, and pepper. Cook,
stirring occasionally, until veggies are softened and lightly browned,
~{7-10%minutes}.

Add @crushed tomatoes{1%unit}, 1/4 cup water, and 1/2 tsp sugar (1/2 cup water
and 1 tsp sugar for 4). Cook, stirring occasionally, until sauce has slightly
thickened, ~{2-4%minutes}.

> Use pan used for chicken or salmon here.

Meanwhile, heat a small #pot{} over medium heat. Add @precooked polenta{}, plus
1/3 cup water (2/3 cup for 4 servings). Mash with a #potato masher{} until mostly
smooth, ~{30-60%seconds}.

Whisk in @sour cream{1.5%tablespoon}, @cream cheese{2%tablespoon},
@Parmesan cheese{3%tablespoon}, and 1 TBSP butter (2 TBSP for 4); cook,
whisking occasionally, until thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Taste and season with
salt and pepper if desired.

> If polenta seems too thick, add water 1 TBSP at a time until it reaches
> desired consistency.

Meanwhile, halve and toast @ciabatta bread{1}.

Cut ciabatta on a diagonal into triangles and drizzle with @olive oil{}.

Divide polenta and ragù between shallow #bowls{} in separate sections. Serve
ciabatta on the side.

> Slice chicken crosswise (no need to slice salmon!). Serve chicken or salmon
> atop polenta.

> Poultry is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.